english:
  title: In Praise of Minister Kim
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    His noble character echoes the virtues of his ancestors,
    His magnanimous spirit subdues the frivolous ways of the world.
    He admires the refined leisure of Xie An upon Eastern Mountain,
    His countenance shines with the lustrous beauty of Chen Ping.

    At times he drinks a thousand cups without faltering,
    At times he sits in dignified silence throughout the day without dispute.
    Sweet springs and auspicious grasses,
    Auspicious clouds and fortunate stars—
    Though such wonders are rare in this world,
    Yet Minister Kim stands as a human treasure,
    A sign that the age has entered into great peace.
  footnotes:
    - Xie An (謝安) was a celebrated official and aesthete of the Eastern Jin who famously withdrew to Eastern Mountain (東山) for leisure and refined pursuits, becoming an ideal of cultured retirement.
    - Chen Ping (陳平) was a renowned strategist and statesman of the Han dynasty, celebrated for his exceptional wisdom and composure.
    - The imagery of sweet springs, auspicious grasses, auspicious clouds, and fortunate stars draws from classical Chinese auspicious portents believed to appear during eras of peace and virtuous rule.
